The neon-drenched smog of Neo-Borinquen in the year 2150 tasted of ozone and dying kelp. Jose Lanz stood on the precipice of the floating seawall, his amber eyes reflecting the sickly, pulsing magenta of the city’s failing holographic advertisements. Below him, the ocean gnawed at the city’s titanium tethers, which were flaking away under the relentless creep of the Crimson Blight—a synthetic, iron-eating bacteria that was slowly dragging his home into the Caribbean abyss. 

Jose wiped a bead of sweat from his forehead, his skin the rich, deep umber of roasted cacao, gleaming under the artificial lights. He ran a trembling hand through his crown of tight, springy coils, now heavily dusted with the silver of chronal-stress. Around his neck hung a digital *cemí*, a holographic projection of the ancient Taíno spirit stone his abuela had given him, humming with a soft, rhythmic pulse that mimicked the heartbeat of the ocean. He was a son of the Gran Caribe, carrying the blood of the indigenous Ostionoid people and the Afro-descendants who had survived the Great Floods, yet he was watching his heritage drown all over again.

Historical archives traced the Crimson Blight’s genesis to a singular, anomalous event: a subterranean fire in the limestone caves of ancient Borikén in the year 1000 CE. The fire had fundamentally altered the cave’s microbiome, birthing the dormant spores that would eventually mutate and devour the 22nd century. 

Jose was going to snuff out the spark before it could catch.

He stepped into the chronosphere. The machine shrieked, a sound like tearing metal and screaming gulls. Reality fractured. Jose’s stomach plummeted as the neon smog dissolved into a blinding smear of ultraviolet light. The air grew thick, tasting of crushed mint and raw copper, and then, with a concussive *crack* that rattled his teeth, he was thrown onto damp earth.

Jose gasped, his lungs suddenly flooding with air so pure and heavy it felt like drinking sweet water. 

He was in the year 1000. 

Rising to his feet, Jose marveled at the untamed, emerald embrace of his ancestral island. Towering ceiba trees, their massive roots gripping the earth like the knuckles of ancient gods, pierced a canopy so thick it filtered the tropical sun into a cathedral of golden, dappled light. The air was a symphony of life: the trill of unseen coquís, the distant, rhythmic crash of the virgin Atlantic, and the sweet, intoxicating perfume of wild orchids and wet soil. It was Borikén, unbroken and sacred. A profound ache bloomed in Jose’s chest. He whispered a quiet prayer to Yemayá, touching his digital *cemí*, asking the mother of the sea to guide his hands.

Consulting his wrist-comp, he navigated the dense foliage until he found the gaping, jagged maw of the Camuy cave system. He descended into the cool, subterranean dark, his suit’s shoulder-lamps cutting through the gloom. Stalactites hung like the fangs of a leviathan, dripping crystalline moisture into echoing subterranean pools. 

Deep within the cavern’s belly, he found it. A dry pocket of ancient, highly flammable guano and petrified wood. And there, near the ceiling, a fracture in the limestone where a single, concentrated beam of midday sunlight was acting as a magnifying glass, focusing onto the dry tinder. A thin wisp of smoke was just beginning to curl. The Great Ignition was seconds away.

"Not today," Jose muttered. 

He unholstered his cryo-suppressant canister. He didn't want to risk a physical disruption that might cause a cave-in, so he aimed the nozzle at the tinder and squeezed the trigger. A thick, hissing cloud of barium-laced, sub-zero chemical foam erupted from the canister, instantly smothering the smoke and freezing the tinder into a block of harmless, frosty ice. 

Jose exhaled, a shaky breath of triumph. The timeline was secure. The Blight would never be born. The floating cities of 2150 would stand eternal. 

He tapped the recall sequence on his wrist-comp. The cavern dissolved into the violent, tearing vortex of the time-stream.

When the blinding light faded, Jose collapsed to his knees on the grated metal floor of the chronosphere. The air was instantly foul again, heavy with the stench of ozone and rotting kelp. He looked up, expecting to see the gleaming, restored titanium of the seawall.

Instead, the metal was bleeding. 

The Crimson Blight was still there, thicker than before, eating away at the structural struts in horrific, rusted scabs. The holographic ads still flickered their sickly magenta. Nothing had changed. 

Panic, cold and sharp, seized his throat. Jose scrambled to the main console, his dark fingers flying across the haptic interface. He pulled up the deep-core chemical analysis of the Blight, cross-referencing it with the historical archives of the year 1000 CE cave deposits. 

The screen populated with molecular structures. Jose’s amber eyes widened, his breath hitching as the data locked into place. 

The Crimson Blight wasn't born from a natural fire. The historical "ash" found in the year 1000 cave strata wasn't wood ash at all. The molecular signature of the iron-eating bacteria was a perfect, undeniable match for the synthetic, barium-laced cryo-foam he had just sprayed in the cave. The freezing agent had reacted with the iron-rich limestone, creating a dormant, synthetic spore that had waited a millennium to feed on refined titanium.

Jose slumped back against the console, the hum of his digital *cemí* suddenly sounding like a mournful dirge. He stared at his hands, the hands that had just doomed his world. 

There was no changing the past, because the past was already built from the ruins of his future. He hadn't traveled back in time to prevent the Great Ignition; he had traveled back to become it. The Ouroboros had swallowed its tail, and as the seawall groaned under the weight of the dying city, Jose realized with crushing certainty that he was the teeth.
